Predicting outcome of Professional Tennis Matches with KNN Classifier¶

Introduction¶

The ATP Tour is a worldwide top-tier tennis tour for men organized by the Association of Tennis Professionals. The ATP Tour comprises ATP Masters 1000, ATP 500, and ATP 250, and the higher the numbers behind, the higher rank of the tournaments. We’ve done research on the probability of winning, and it is mentioned that playing the first serve successfully helps to win the game. Hence, our project will use the ATP tour data from 2017 to 2019 to analyze whether the players’ age, height and performance during the game is related to the result of the game. We would like to predict whether or not a player can win the game based on their height, age and performance during the game. We will construct several models using different predictors, and include the best two predictors into our final model. The question we want to answer is if we can build a classifier to accurately predict the outcome of a tennis match based on height, age, and other tennis statistics. We will construct several models using different predictors, and include the best predictors (up to three) for our final model. The data we will be basing our analysis on is from https://github.com/JeffSackmann/tennis_atp, specifically using the data from 2017-2019. We will be mutating this data to include only a subset of columns to use as predictors (listed in the exploratory data analysis section), along with the outcome of the match.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We first download the dataset as CSV file and read it into R. For this analysis, we want to use the following columns as predictors: height (cm), age (years), number of aces, number of double faults, number of serve points, number of first serves made, number of first serve points won, number of second serve points won, number of serve games, number of break points faced, and number of break points saved. We notice that each row containts match data that includes data for the winning player and losing player, so we first create two separate tibbles to store data for winners and losers. These tibbles are merged after columns are renamed. After splitting the data into training and test sets, we calculated the number of observations of each class, the means of our predictors, and the number of missing values in our training set, which are all stored in different tables. Finally, we made simple scatter plots to see how our variables related with one another. Our initial assumption is that players with lower ages would have more wins, so we formed scatter plots with age on the x-axis and another predictor on the y-axis. We did not create plots for all the possible combinations of predictors, as we only wanted to see if our intuition towards age aligns with the data. From the plots we made, there does not seem to be any obvious clustering of winning data points near the lower ranges of age. We plan to use variable selection techniques to verify if age is a predictor worth including in our model (explained more in the methods section)

# Load and mutate data
tennis_data_2019<-read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffSackmann/tennis_atp/master/atp_matches_2019.csv')
tennis_data_2018<-read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffSackmann/tennis_atp/master/atp_matches_2018.csv')
tennis_data_2017<-read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffSackmann/tennis_atp/master/atp_matches_2017.csv')
tennis_data <- bind_rows(tennis_data_2019, tennis_data_2018, tennis_data_2017)
winner_data <- select(tennis_data, c(winner_name, 
                      winner_age, 
                      winner_ht, 
                      w_ace, 
                      w_df, 
                      w_svpt, 
                      w_1stIn, 
                      w_1stWon, 
                      w_SvGms, 
                      w_bpSaved, 
                      w_bpFaced)) %>%
                rename(name=winner_name,
                      age=winner_age,
                      height=winner_ht,
                      aces=w_ace,
                      double_faults=w_df,
                      serve_points=w_svpt,
                      first_serves_made=w_1stIn,
                      first_serve_points=w_1stWon,
                      serve_games=w_SvGms,
                      break_points_saved=w_bpSaved,
                      break_points_faced=w_bpFaced) %>%
                add_column(match_result='win')
loser_data <- select(tennis_data, c(loser_name, 
                      loser_age, 
                      loser_ht, 
                      l_ace, 
                      l_df, 
                      l_svpt, 
                      l_1stIn, 
                      l_1stWon, 
                      l_SvGms, 
                      l_bpSaved, 
                      l_bpFaced)) %>%
                rename(name=loser_name,
                      age=loser_age,
                      height=loser_ht,
                      aces=l_ace,
                      double_faults=l_df,
                      serve_points=l_svpt,
                      first_serves_made=l_1stIn,
                      first_serve_points=l_1stWon,
                      serve_games=l_SvGms,
                      break_points_saved=l_bpSaved,
                      break_points_faced=l_bpFaced) %>%
                add_column(match_result='lose')
tennis_data_mod <- bind_rows(winner_data, loser_data)

Methods¶

The data analysis will be conducted using a K-nearest neighbors model, with only certain columns from the data set being included in the analysis. The columns that will be used initially are a player’s age, height and several statistics specific to a winner’s match performance: w_ace, w_df, w_svpt, w_1stIn, w_1stWon, w_2ndWon, w_SvGms, w_bpSaved and w_bpFaced. From these variables, forward selection will be performed to create the KNN model with up to 3 predictors that provides the greatest prediction accuracy. Cross-validation will then be performed to determine the number of neighbors (K) that maximizes accuracy. The results will then be visualized on a scatterplot with the predictor variables on the axes and the points colour-coded for match winners.

Expected Outcomes and Significance¶

Through this analysis, we expect to find players with higher positive tennis stats (ex. higher number of aces, service points), greater height, and younger age would be more likely to win and vice versa. Our findings could help discover which factors are most important for winning in professional tennis matches. Based on the importance of the tennis stats, coaches could help build an efficient training plan for athletes. For example, if a high number of service aces seems to correlate with players that win matches, a coach may prioritize perfecting a player's serve over other techniques. Some questions our analysis could lead to is discovering other predictors that could better predict the outcome of a match.
